'''Henry Evans Maude''', [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] (1 October 1906 &ndash; 4 November 2006) was a British [[civil servant]], [[historian]] and [[anthropologist]].
Maude was born in [[Bankipur (Bihar)|Bankipore]], [[British Raj|India]].<ref name="JCC">MAUDE, Henry Evans (1926) died on 4 November 2006, aged 100. [http://www.jesus.cam.ac.uk/alumni/publications/Annual%20Report%202007.pdf One Hundred and Third Annual Report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607200759/http://www.jesus.cam.ac.uk/alumni/publications/Annual%20Report%202007.pdf|date=7 June 2011}}, Jesus College, Cambridge, 2007.</ref> Educated at [[Highgate School]] from 1921-25, and [[Jesus College, Cambridge|Jesus College]], [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], Maude represented India at [[Shooting sport|rifle-shooting]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ed. Boreham|first1=J.Y.|title=Highgate School Register 1838-1938|page=319|edition=4th}}</ref>
He spent the years 1929-48 working as a civil servant and administrator in various [[Pacific Islands]], in particular the [[British colony]] of the [[Gilbert and Ellice Islands]], serving as [[Resident Commissioner]] from 1946-49. From 1948-57, he worked for the [[South Pacific Commission]].{{cn|date=December 2017}}
From 1957-61, he was a Research Fellow at the [[Research School of Pacific and Asian Studies]] (RSPAS), which is part of the [[Australian National University]] in [[Canberra]].<ref>{{citation|last=Maude|first=H.E.|isbn=0-8047-1106-2|publisher=Stanford University Press and Australian National University Press|title=Slavers in Paradise: The Peruvian Slave Trade in Polynesia, 1862-1864|year=1981}}<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref> He has published widely on aspects of Pacific Islands history, was a co-founder of the ''Journal of Pacific History'', and played an important role in establishing the [[Pacific Manuscripts Bureau]].<ref name="JCC"/>
==Personal life== He was the husband of [[Honor Maude|Honor Courtney Maude (née King)]], a British-Australian authority on [[Pacific Islander|Oceanic]] [[string figure]]s. She predeceased him, dying in 2001 in [[Canberra]], aged 95.<ref>[http://tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/00223340120075632?journalCode=cjph20 Honor Courtney Maude (née King) obituary], tandfonline.com; accessed 20 December 2017.</ref>
==Death and legacy== Maude died, aged 100, on 4 November 2006.<ref name="JCC"/> The bulk of Maude's personal papers are held at the [[Barr Smith Library]] at the [[University of Adelaide]], where an extensive set of pages devoted to his life and work can be found. He published the work of Sir [[Arthur Grimble]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060504021751/http://www.adelaide.edu.au/library/special/maude.html Papers of Henry Evans and Honor Courtney Maude, 1904-1999], Library of the University of Adelaide.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed, if any --></ref>
==Bibliography== * Doug Munro, "Harry Maude—Loyal lieutenant, incurable romantic", ''The Ivory Tower and Beyond : Participant Historians of the Pacific'', Newcastle upon Tyne, Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2009, pp. 171-242. *{{citation | last = Woodburn | first = Susan | isbn = 978-1-86333-245-3 | publisher = Crawford House Publishers | title = Where our hearts still lie: Harry and Honor Maude in the Pacific islands | year = 2003}}. *{{citation | last = Gunson | first = Niel | publisher = Oxford University Press | title = The Changing Pacific: Essays in Honour of H. E. Maude | year = 1978}}. *{{citation | last = Maude | first = H. E. | isbn = | publisher = Melbourne, Oxford University Press | title = Of Islands & Men | year = 1968}}. * Maude, H. E. (1981) ''Slavers in Paradise; The Peruvian labour trade in Polynesia, 1862-1864'', Canberra, Australian National University Press, {{ISBN|0-7081-1607-8}}
