{{for|the businessman|Robin Jeffrey (businessman)}} {{use dmy dates|date=March 2013}} {{use British English|date=March 2013}}
'''Robin Bannerman Jeffrey''' is a Canadian-born professor. His primary research interest is the modern history and politics of India, especially with reference the northern area of [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] and [[Kerala]] in the south. He is also interested in Indian [[media studies]] and [[development studies]].<ref name="aii">{{cite web |url=http://www.aii.unimelb.edu.au/robin-jeffrey |title=Robin Jeffrey |publisher=Australia India Institute |accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref>
==Life== Robin Jeffrey was born in Canada.<ref name="et" /> He studied first at the [[University of Victoria]], [[British Columbia]], Canada, from where he graduated with a BA degree.<ref name="aii" /> He was awarded a D.Phil in modern Indian history by the [[University of Sussex]], England, in 1973 and had previously worked as a school teacher in [[Chandigarh]], India, for the Regional Institute of English and the [[Canadian University Service Overseas]] between 1967 and 1969.<ref name="aii" /><ref name="isas" /> His first employment had been in 1963 as a sports writer for a small daily newspaper in Canada.<ref>{{cite book |title=India's Newspaper Revolution: Capitalism, Politics and the Indian-Language Press, 1977-99 |location=London |publisher=C. Hurst & Co. |year=2000 |first=Robin |last=Jeffrey |page=Rear cover |isbn=9781850654346}}</ref>
Jeffrey took up a position as a [[Research Fellow]] at the [[Australian National University]] upon completion of his doctorate. He has taught at that institution in [[Canberra]] during two different periods. He taught politics at [[La Trobe University]], [[Melbourne]], Australia, between 1979 and 2005, where he became a professor.<ref name="aii" /><ref name="isas" /> In 2002, he was elected a Fellow of the [[Australian Academy of Social Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/profile.php?id=414 |publisher=Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia |title=Robin Jeffrey |accessdate=24 March 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420174151/http://www.assa.edu.au/fellows/profile.php?id=414 |archivedate=20 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> having been previously elected a Fellow of the [[Australian Academy of the Humanities]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web |title=Robin Jefrrey: Curriculum Vitae |publisher=National University of Singapore |accessdate=24 March 2013 |url=http://www.ari.nus.edu.sg/docs/CV/RobinJeffrey-CV.pdf}}</ref>
{{as of|2018}}, Jeffrey is an [[Emeritus Professor]] of La Trobe University and the Australian National University. He chairs an advisory panel of the [[Australia India Institute]] within the [[University of Melbourne]], Australia.<ref name="aii" /> He was been a visiting research professor at the [[Institute of South Asian Studies]], based at the [[National University of Singapore]], since 2009.<ref name="isas">{{cite web |url=http://www.isas.nus.edu.sg/ResearchMember.aspx?MemId=b49c61c0-3b9a-4fe4-9500-7a0745738045 |title=ISAS Research Team: Professor Robin Jeffrey |publisher=Institute of South Asian Studies, National University of Singapore |accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref>
In 2011, when concentrating on media and development studies, Jeffrey said that {{quote|The mobile phone is the most disruptive individual device since shoes. Shoes gave people who owned them the ability to do things they could not do before and that people without shoes could not do. If you want to control people and make them inferior, take away their shoes.<ref name="et">{{cite news |title=Mobile phones most disruptive device since shoes: Robin Jeffrey |newspaper=The Economic Times |date=29 July 2011 |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-07-29/news/29829269_1_shoes-autonomy-big-people |accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref>}}
